        ],
        [
          "Clustering",
          "Higher Education",
          "Peer Learning",
          "364 first-year students",
          "All courses in the Behavioral and Social Sciences Department of the University of Groningen",
          "Survey for Socio-Economic Details,\nSurvey for Social Behavior,\nPre-University Academic Records",
          "Pintrich’s SRL Framework",
          "[First-Year Student, Moving Out, Financial Support, Mentor Support, , Peer Support, Friends, Help/Advice Seeking, Collaboration, Self-Efficacy, Weighted Average Mark for Fall Semester,  Weighted Average Mark for Spring Semester, Weighted Average Mark for First Year}",
          "Authors employed Path Analysis to explore the best way in which to fill missing values. \n\nIn addition, the authors measure correlation between the different predictors. ",
          "Multi-Level Regression Analysis",
          "Model was found to be statistically significant to describe student performance.",
          "3",
          "Low Achievers\n\nAverage Achievers\n\nHigh achievers: Having friends shows a positive relationship with success.\n",
          "Peer and Faculty capital contribute to explaining student success.\n\nFamily support was not shown to be relevant at this level, likely because students without family support often fail at reaching the undergraduate level. \n\nBeing in a small group with similar peers does not seem to be benefical for either loiw or average attainment students.\n\nFirst semester success is highly indicative of later success, which means that using this as an early-warning system may be relevant.\n\nAuthors argue for the buiding of fostering development of social connections between different levels of achievers in a way that helps low achievers find the social capital that helps them perform.\n\n ",
          "Authors do the separation at the level of the dependent variablein 3 categories.\n\nEffect of social circles and having friends was remarkably higher for high-achieving students → suggesting that social interactions are more benefical in this context than they are for lower achieving students. ",
          "Study focuses only on access to social capital via number of friends and not social networks themselves.\n\nUse of self-reports to measure support without any direct behavioral data.\n\nHomogenous sample of Behavioral and Social Sciences students.\n\n"
        ]
      ],
      "index": 5
    }
  ],
